In RNA-Seq, Salmon, STAR, and HISAT2 are used for different purposes depending on your analysis goal, speed requirements, and downstream applications.

1. Use Salmon → when you mainly want gene/transcript quantification

Best for:

Differential expression analysis

Large datasets

Fast processing

Transcript-level quantification


Why:

Uses pseudo-alignment/lightweight mapping

Much faster and requires less storage

Produces transcript abundance directly

Very accurate for expression estimation


Typical workflow: FASTQ → Salmon → tximport → DESeq2/edgeR/limma

Use Salmon when:

You do bulk RNA-seq DEG analysis

You do not need BAM alignment files

You do not need variant calling or splice visualization

You want computational efficiency


Avoid Salmon if you need:

IGV visualization

Novel splice junction discovery

Mutation/SNV analysis

Fusion detection



---

2. Use STAR → when you need highly accurate full alignment

Best for:

Splice junction detection

Alternative splicing

Fusion gene analysis

Single-cell RNA-seq

IGV visualization

Downstream BAM-based analyses


Why:

Extremely fast full aligner

Very accurate splice-aware mapping

Generates high-quality BAM files

Excellent for complex transcriptomes


Typical workflow: FASTQ → STAR → featureCounts/HTSeq → DESeq2

Use STAR when:

You need BAM files

You want to inspect reads in IGV

You study isoforms/splicing

You perform fusion detection

You need maximum alignment sensitivity


Limitations:

Requires high RAM (~30–40 GB for human genome indexing)

Larger output files



---

3. Use HISAT2 → when you want efficient alignment with lower RAM

Best for:

Standard bulk RNA-seq

Systems with limited computational resources

Reference-based alignment


Why:

Memory efficient

Splice-aware aligner

Good balance of speed and accuracy

Easier on laptops/workstations


Typical workflow: FASTQ → HISAT2 → featureCounts → DESeq2

Use HISAT2 when:

You need BAM files but have limited RAM

You are doing routine DEG analysis

You want reliable genome alignment

You work on standard bulk RNA-seq projects


Limitations:

Slightly slower/less sensitive than STAR for complex splicing

Less preferred for advanced isoform analysis



---

Quick Decision Guide

Goal	Recommended Tool

Fast DEG analysis	Salmon
Transcript quantification	Salmon
BAM file generation	STAR / HISAT2
IGV visualization	STAR / HISAT2
Alternative splicing	STAR
Fusion detection	STAR
Low RAM system	HISAT2
Large-scale projects	Salmon
Standard bulk RNA-seq	HISAT2 or Salmon
Single-cell RNA-seq	STAR



---

Common Modern Practice

Many current studies prefer:

Salmon + tximport + DESeq2 for fast expression analysis

STAR for alignment-heavy analyses

HISAT2 when computational resources are limited


For your kind of bulk RNA-seq DEG workflows with PCA, batch correction, heatmaps, and DESeq2:

Use Salmon if expression analysis is the main goal.

Use STAR/HISAT2 if you also want IGV visualization or read-level inspection.
